title: A Phase 3, Multi-Center, Randomized, Double-Blind Placebo-Controlled Study To Evaluate The Safety And Tolerability Of Dimebon (PF-01913539) For Up To 26-Weeks In Patients With Mild To Moderate Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: This is a multi-center, randomized, double-blind placebo-controlled safety study conducted in 2 study cohorts. In Cohort 1, subjects with Alzheimer's disease (n=250) will receive Dimebon 20 mg or placebo TID for 26 weeks. In Cohort 2 AD subjects (n=500) will be treated with Dimebon 20 mg or placebo TID for 12 weeks After completion of the randomized portion of the study, subjects in both Cohorts will have the opportunity to enroll in a Dimebon open label extension study.

outcomeMeasures.description: Abnormal clinically significant vital signs included absolute systolic blood pressure (BP) values: less than (\<) 90 millimeter of mercury (mmHg), maximum increase or decrease of greater than or equal to (\>=) 30 mmHg from baseline; absolute diastolic BP value: \<50 mmHg, maximum increase or decrease of \>=20 mmHg from baseline; absolute heart rate values: \>120 beats per minute (bpm).

limitationsAndCaveats.description: This safety study did not specify primary or secondary outcome measures. Relevant summaries of all safety assessments are thus provided. Urine blood abnormalities seen are deemed due to interference with dipstick test by a metabolite of dimebon.

certainAgreement.otherDetails: Pfizer has the right to review disclosures, requesting a delay of less than 60 days. Investigator will postpone single center publications until after disclosure of pooled data (all sites), less than 12 months from study completion/termination at all participating sites. Investigator may not disclose previously undisclosed confidential information other than study results.

explanation_target: Reason: The trial tests Dimebon (latrepirdine) in mild–moderate AD patients with the intent to evaluate safety/tolerability and (as in earlier studies) effects on cognition and global function. The available literature describes dimebon as an orally active small molecule (originally an antihistamine) thought to modulate neurotransmission and stabilize mitochondrial function rather than being a biologic that directly targets amyloid or tau pathology. citeturn0search4turn0search6

Act: Key extracted details — drug: Dimebon (latrepirdine, PF-01913539); dose: 20 mg TID vs placebo; study purpose: safety/tolerability in AD with earlier trials assessing cognitive and global endpoints. Dimebon is a small molecule (not a monoclonal antibody or vaccine). Phase 3 development ultimately failed to show cognitive benefit over placebo. citeturn0search1turn0search4

Reflect: Mapping to the category definitions — because dimebon is a small-molecule drug whose proposed action was symptomatic (neurotransmitter/mitochondrial modulation) and it was developed to improve cognition/global function rather than as a directed anti-amyloid or anti-tau biologic, it best fits the 'Cognitive enhancer' category. Some preclinical reports noted effects on amyloid measures in animals, but there is no clear primary disease-pathology–targeted mechanism (amyloid/tau) for dimebon in humans. Therefore 'Cognitive enhancer' is the most appropriate classification. citeturn0search3turn0search4turn0search1

explanation_agent: Reason: Dimebon (latrepirdine) is an orally active small molecule developed as a symptomatic cognitive enhancer in AD; its most reliably reported pharmacology in independent reviews is modulation/inhibition of neurotransmitter receptors (not a direct anti-amyloid or anti-tau biologic). citeturn0search4turn0search6

Act: Key extracted details — drug: Dimebon (latrepirdine), small molecule 20 mg TID in Phase 3; sponsors described a proposed mitochondrial/stabilizing effect but independent analyses conclude its likely clinical pharmacology involves histamine H1 and serotonin 5-HT6 (neurotransmitter) receptor actions; Phase 3 development failed to show efficacy. citeturn0search0turn0search4turn0search3

Reflect: Mapping to CADRO — because the dominant, evidence-supported mechanism is neurotransmitter receptor modulation (symptomatic cognitive enhancement) rather than a primary disease-modifying target (amyloid, tau, inflammation, etc.), the best CADRO fit is D) Neurotransmitter Receptors. Mitochondrial/bioenergetic hypotheses were proposed by sponsors but lack a clear molecular target and thus do not outweigh the neurotransmitter-receptor evidence. citeturn0search6turn0search4
